[1.9 History of Database Systems]
	- 1950s and early 1960s
		-> magnetic tapes were developed for data storage.

		-> tapes could be read only sequentially, and data sizes were much larger than main memory;
			+ data-processing programs were forced to process data in a particular order by reading and merging data from tapes and card decks.

	- Late 1960s and early 1970s
		-> hard disks allowed direct access to data.

		-> any location on disk could be accessed in just tens of milliseconds.
			+ data were freed from the tyranny of sequentiality.

		-> network and hierarchical data modesl were developed
			+ data structures such as lists and trees to be stored on disk.

	- Late 1970s and 1980s
		-> Initial commercial relational database systems, such as IBM DB2, Oracle, Ingres, and DEC Rdb.

		-> relational databases ahd become competitive with network and hierarchical db systems even in the area of performance.

		* low level tasks are carried out automatically by the db system.

		* 1980s much research on parallel and distributed databases, as well as initial work on object-oriented databases.

	- 1990s
		-> SQL language was designed primarily for decision support applications, query-intensive.

		-> explosive growth of the World Wide Web.
			+ Databases were deployed much more extensively than ever before.

		-> high transaction-processing rates, as well as very high reliability and 24 X 7 availability(24 hours a day, 7 days a week = no downtime for scheduled maintenance activities)

	- 2000s
		-> XML emerged as data-exchange standard.
		-> JSON more compact data-exchange format well suited for storing objects from JavaScript or other programming languages grew important.

		-> such data were stored in relational database systems as support for the XML and JSON formats was added to the major commercial systems.

		-> Open-source db systems, such as PostgreSQL and MySQL saw increased use.

		-> Auto-admin features were added to db systems to allow automatic reconfiguration to adapt to changing workloads.

		* Social network platforms grew at a rapid pace, creating a need to manage data about connections between people and their posted data.
			+ led to the development of graph databases.

		-> use of data analytics and data mining in enterprises became ubiquitous.

		-> "NoSql" model of "eventual consistency" allowed for distributed copies of data to be inconsistent as long they would eventually converge in the absence of further updates.

	- 2010s
		-> "cloud" services that host data for various clients in multiple, widely distributed server farms.

		-> "software as a service"(SAAS)
			+ the vendor not only stores the data but also runs the application software.

			* security breaches, data ownership problem in cases where a government requests access to data.

		


